Webster Bank Names John R. Ciulla Its New President - Hartford Courant




























































Business 



Webster Bank Names New President








Webster Financial Corporation
John R. Ciulla of Webster Financial Corporation.
John R. Ciulla of Webster Financial Corporation. (Webster Financial Corporation)

Kenneth R. GosselinContact ReporterProperty Line

Webster Bank names John R. Cuilla its new president




Webster Bank named a new president late Wednesday, a likely successor to the longtime chief executive and son of the bank's founder.John R. Ciulla, 50, was named president of the Waterbury-based bank and its holding company, Webster Financial Corp., after more than a decade at the bank, most recently as executive vice president and head of commercial banking.As president, Ciulla will continue to lead the commercial bank and will add responsibilities for community banking, Webster's private bank and marketing.Webster's current president, Joseph J. Savage, has been appointed executive vice chairman and will continue to oversee human resources and programs for leadership development, incentive compensation and employee engagement. He will also continue to serve on the bank's board.Savage, 63, was named president in late 2013, after the abrupt resignation of Gerald Plush from the post. Plush had been viewed as the successor to the chief executive post.The chief executive post is now held by James C. Smith, son of the bank's founder, Harold W. Smith. Smith, 66, has not announced any plans for retirement.



KENNETH R. GOSSELIN


Waterbury-based Webster Financial Corp. on Thursday reported flat profits in the first quarter, with higher loan and deposit growth offset by a dip in lending income and other fees.

The parent of Webster Bank said net income available to common shareholders was $47.1 million, or 52 cents a diluted...



Waterbury-based Webster Financial Corp. on Thursday reported flat profits in the first quarter, with higher loan and deposit growth offset by a dip in lending income and other fees.

The parent of Webster Bank said net income available to common shareholders was $47.1 million, or 52 cents a diluted... (KENNETH R. GOSSELIN)

"This is part of the bank's succession planning," Robert Guenther, a Webster spokesman, said Wednesday. "We are preparing the bank for the next generation of leaders for when they are in the driver's seat."Both Ciulla and Savage will report to Smith, who also serves as chairman.

If Ciulla ascends to chief executive, he would be the first to hold that role outside of the Smith family. Webster recently celebrated the 80th anniversary of its founding.Ciulla joined Webster in 2004 as senior vice president of middle market banking and later served in a variety of management positions, including chief credit risk officer from 2008 to 2010. As executive vice president and head of middle market banking from 2011 to 2013, he was responsible for several business units. He was promoted to lead commercial banking in 2014.



KENNETH R. GOSSELIN


The chief executive of Waterbury-based Webster Financial Corp. received a compensation package of $3.5 million, boosted by a higher cash incentive payment tied to the bank's financial performance, a shareholder proxy filed Friday shows.

The package for Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James...



The chief executive of Waterbury-based Webster Financial Corp. received a compensation package of $3.5 million, boosted by a higher cash incentive payment tied to the bank's financial performance, a shareholder proxy filed Friday shows.

The package for Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James... (KENNETH R. GOSSELIN)

Previously, Ciulla worked at The Bank of New York and practiced law in New York."John's promotion to president recognizes his outstanding leadership and commercial banking's consistently strong performance," Smith said.As head of commercial banking, Ciulla drove strong revenue and earnings growth, and he continued to expand the reach of the unit's lending activities, Smith said.Smith praised Savage's contributions as president, including initiatives to make Webster the highest performing mid-size bank in the country, as measured by financial perfornance, customer satisfaction and other areas."He will contine to work closely with me in formulating strategy and will lead key external client initiatives," Smith said.

